<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike still wines, Prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically across quality levels, with most styles designed for immediate enjoyment rather than long-term cellaring.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> reaches peak drinking within 1-2 years of release, as the fresh pear and apple characteristics begin to fade beyond this window. <strong>Prosecco DOCG</strong> from Conegliano Valdobbiadene can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, with premium cuvées like those from Cartizze maintaining their mineral-driven complexity even longer. <strong>Franciacorta DOCG</strong>, produced via méthode champenoise, offers the greatest aging potential at 8-12 years, developing toasty, brioche-like autolytic characters that rival Champagne.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>As Prosecco ages, the bright citrus and floral aromatics gradually give way to more complex honeyed and nutty notes. The signature frizzante bubbles become finer and more integrated, while acidity remains the structural backbone. However, the characteristic fresh fruit intensity—Prosecco's greatest asset—diminishes significantly after optimal drinking windows.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store Prosecco bottles horizontally at 50-55°F with 60-70% humidity, away from light and vibration. Unlike still wines, sparkling wines are more sensitive to temperature fluctuations, which can affect bubble quality and accelerate aging.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>
<p>Well-aged Prosecco develops deeper golden hues and more persistent mousse. The aromatics shift from primary fruit to secondary honey and almond notes. Signs of spoilage include browning, flat bubbles, oxidized sherry-like aromas, or harsh acidic bite without fruit balance.</p>

