  <h2>Food Pairing Guide</h2>

<p>Prosecco's bright acidity and effervescence create natural flavor bridges with a wide range of foods, making it one of the most versatile sparkling wines for pairing. The wine's crisp minerality and subtle fruit notes complement both delicate and rich dishes, while its bubbles cleanse the palate and cut through oils and fats.</p>

<h3>Classic Venetian Regional Pairings</h3>
<p>In its native Veneto region, Prosecco traditionally accompanies <strong>cicchetti</strong> (Venetian small plates) featuring baccalà mantecato (whipped salt cod) and sarde in saor (sweet and sour sardines). The wine's acidity perfectly balances these preserved fish preparations, while its effervescence lifts the rich, oily textures.</p>

<h3>Perfect Pairing Matches</h3>
<ul class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
  <li><strong>Fresh oysters and shellfish</strong> – The wine's mineral backbone mirrors the briny ocean flavors, while bubbles enhance the shellfish's natural sweetness</li>
  <li><strong>Prosciutto di Parma with melon</strong> – Prosecco's acidity cuts through the ham's saltiness while echoing the melon's delicate fruit notes</li>
  <li><strong>Fried calamari or tempura</strong> – The effervescence cleanses oils while the wine's crispness prevents palate fatigue</li>
  <li><strong>Fresh mozzarella caprese salad</strong> – The wine's bright acidity complements tomatoes' natural acids and enhances basil's herbal qualities</li>
  <li><strong>Sushi and sashimi</strong> – Light bubbles won't overpower delicate fish, while the wine's clean finish resets the palate between pieces</li>
</ul>

<h3>Versatile Everyday Options</h3>
<p>For casual dining, Prosecco pairs beautifully with <strong>cheese and charcuterie boards</strong>, particularly soft cheeses like Taleggio or fresh goat cheese. Pizza margherita becomes elevated with Prosecco's ability to balance tomato acidity and cut through melted cheese.</p>

<h3>Special Occasion Selections</h3>
<p>Elevate celebrations by pairing Prosecco Superiore DOCG with <strong>lobster risotto</strong> or <strong>truffle pasta</strong>. The wine's more complex structure and longer lees aging complement these luxurious dishes without overwhelming their nuanced flavors. For dessert, try Prosecco with <strong>fresh berry tarts</strong> – the wine's natural fruit notes create harmonious flavor echoes while its dryness prevents sweetness overload.</p>

